Assignment

Week 4

In this assignment I make use of data from a personal activity monitoring device. This device collects data at 5 minute intervals through out the day. The data consists of two months of data from an anonymous individual collected during the months of October and November, 2012 and include the number of steps taken in 5 minute intervals each day.

The variables included in this dataset are:

steps: Number of steps taking in a 5-minute interval (missing values are coded as NA}NA)
date: The date on which the measurement was taken in YYYY-MM-DD format
interval: Identifier for the 5-minute interval in which measurement was taken

#Transform time variable to POSIXct
df <- dl
df$day <- weekdays(as.Date(dl$date))
df$DateTime <- as.POSIXct(dl$date, format="%Y-%m-%d")

#Drop NAs
df1 <- dl[!is.na(dl$steps),]
#Aggregate data
sumData <- aggregate(df1$steps ~df1$date, FUN=sum, )
colnames(sumData) <- c("Date", "Steps")

2. Histogram showing steps taken per day

#Plot histogram showing number of steps taken per day
hist(sumData$Steps, breaks=5, xlab = "Steps", main = "Sum steps per day")

3. Mean and Median number of steps per day

4: Time series plot of the average number of steps taken

library(ggplot2)
library(plyr)
#Calculate average number of steps taken
intervalData <- ddply(df1, .(interval), summarize, Avg = mean(steps))
p <- ggplot(intervalData, aes(x=interval, y=Avg)) 
p + geom_line() + xlab(" 5 minute interval") + ylab("Avg Number of Steps") + ggtitle("Average Number of Steps per Interval")

The 5-minute interval that, on average, contains the maximum number of steps

# maximum steps by interval
maxStep <- max(intervalData$Avg)

# interval containing  maximum avg number of steps
intervalData[intervalData$Avg == maxStep, 1]
## [1] 835

6. Code to describe and show a strategy for imputing missing data

## Strategy: To identify and imppute means for NA values
#Load data
dfMissing <- dl
#Exploing how much missingness ther is in the data
sum(is.na(dfMissing$steps))
## [1] 2304
mean(is.na(dfMissing$steps))
## [1] 0.1311475
#Substituting NAs with mean values
dfMissing$steps[is.na(dfMissing$steps)] <- mean(dfMissing$steps, na.rm=TRUE)
#Checking that we dont have any NAs after imputation
mean(is.na(dfMissing$steps))
## [1] 0

7. Histogram of the total number of steps taken each day after missing values are imputed

#Aggregate variable to calculate the total number of steps taken each day
sumDataMissing <- aggregate(dfMissing$steps ~dfMissing$date, FUN = sum, )
colnames(sumDataMissing) <- c("Date", "Steps")
hist(sumDataMissing$Steps, breaks = 5, main="Histogram Number of steps after imputation", xlab="Steps")

8. Panel plot comparing the average number of steps taken per 5-minute interval across weekdays and weekends

library(timeDate)
library(lattice)
library(ggplot2)
#Load data
dfIntervalWeek <- df1
#Categrize weekdays and Weekends
dfIntervalWeek$DayCategory[isWeekday(df1$date)] <- "Weekday"
dfIntervalWeek$DayCategory[isWeekend(df1$date)] <- "Weekend"

#Calculate Average number of steps taken per 5-minute interval across weekdays and weekend
dfIntervalWeekA <- aggregate(dfIntervalWeek$steps, by=list(dfIntervalWeek$interval, dfIntervalWeek$DayCategory), FUN=mean)
colnames(dfIntervalWeekA) <- c("Interval", "DayCategory", "Steps")

#Plotting the data in a panel
ggplot(dfIntervalWeekA, aes(y = Steps, x = Interval)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = DayCategory)) +
  facet_grid(DayCategory ~ .) +
  ggtitle("Average Number of Steps per Interval Weekend vs Weekday") +
  xlab("Interval ID") +
  ylab("Number of Steps")
